keywords cleric clerics
---
Clerics are divine casters who treat faith as institutional infrastructure rather than personal devotion. The tradition descends from the Solar Court of the Undivided Disk, specifically the Dawn Liturgists and Seal College offices — practitioners who understood religious rites as maintenance procedures for the cosmological machinery containing the Black Sun Shard beneath the Great Pyramid. The Shard Doctrine defines the tradition: the Black Sun Shard is an active metaphysical threat whose documented effects include crops failing under clear skies, the dead rising with incorrect memories, households forgetting bloodlines, and charter stones bearing unreadable inscriptions. Containing it requires continuous institutional attention. The diaspora following the Ninth Meridian Catastrophe scattered covenant-keepers into the crossroads cities carrying Solar Court technical knowledge. The Violet Compact's registry law formalized the tradition's civic standing and created the inner and outer tradition distinction: the outer tradition is fully documented and publicly accessible; the inner tradition maintains the Solar Court's technical Shard-containment inheritance and is transmitted only within lineages of demonstrated commitment. The Hour of Quiet Thunder schism split a restorationist faction (who became ancestors of the Priest path, devoted to direct healing service) from the infrastructuralist faction that remained the cleric tradition proper. The Paladin tradition, originating from temple-guard auxiliaries, aligned institutionally with the infrastructuralist faction during the Violet Compact era, producing the modern Paladin-Cleric alliance. Current Shard containment assessment is based on proxy indicators; direct assessment has been impossible since the Ninth Meridian collapse isolated the Pyramid.

flags MIDGAARD
---
Midgaard's Temple Licensing Compact grants temples chartered status and subjects practitioners to registry requirements. Clerics file practice notices specifying patron deity and service area.
The Sealed Names Apparatus has used temple records as a secondary population tracking source — contested by cleric organizations as violating spiritual privilege.
The Continuity faction relies on major temples as institutional allies; outer tradition public accountability is a useful counterweight to inner tradition classification preferences.
The Reckoning faction has found temple archives containing misclassification evidence from the Ash-and-Iron Decades.
Guard Command's relationship with temple healers is practical: battlefield casualties flow to temple facilities under emergency charter provision.
The inner tradition's Continuity alignment creates friction when Continuity suppresses histories that Jackal Tribunal ethics — part of the Solar Court inheritance — would require honest accounting of.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Temple Circle is one of the five civic institutions formed from the original six founding houses, coordinating religious practice across the city's district-color system.
Kowloon clerics operate under Temple Circle coordination rather than individual temple charter — a more collectively managed environment than the Midgaard model.
Kowloon clerics are more practically oriented than Midgaard counterparts: the city's founding mythology centers the Neon Covenant's collective engineering-and-logistics Ashfall response. Ledger Priest lineage clerics fit most naturally into Kowloon's culture.
Jade Magistracy jurisdiction intersects with Temple Circle authority when religious practice affects civic order — the overlap is managed through established protocol rather than clear boundary, creating periodic coordination problems.
The Temple Circle's district governance role means Kowloon clerics are more deeply embedded in civic administration than in most other cities.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant charter prevents the inner tradition from using its traditional classification authority to suppress information about its own practices within Kiess jurisdiction — sealed warrants from predecessor authorities do not bind Kiess citizens, which means the Solar Court's knowledge classification system does not automatically apply.
Practitioners who wanted to study the Solar Court inheritance without the inner tradition's classification barriers found that Kiess's legal framework protected their access in ways no other city does.
Kiess holds some of the most complete publicly accessible records on pre-Compact cleric practice anywhere in the five-city network.
Wall Command's relationship with cleric practitioners is practical: frontier conditions require reliable healing capacity under emergency circumstances, and clerics operating under Kiess charter enjoy more operational independence than those under other city frameworks.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen clerics serve primarily in disaster-response consecration. The city's chronic emergency posture creates continuous need for death rites, wound blessing, and community-sustaining ceremonial work.
Rakuen clerics are the most practically experienced in high-volume service delivery and the least theoretically sophisticated in the five-city network — the crisis-adapted training model that the diaspora monasteries developed during the Ninth Meridian collapse period is most fully continued in Rakuen's cleric practice.
Ember Warden infrastructure integrates cleric healing capacity formally; clerics operating within Ember Warden auspices follow collective accountability requirements analogous to Warden documentation standards.
The Canopy Compact treats cleric service as a communal resource rather than an individual professional service — practitioners are expected to provide services based on community need rather than individual commission.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's cleric presence operates through the Shrine of the First Claw's adjacent ritual infrastructure — a theologically distinct tradition rooted in the guardian Mafdet tradition (protective executioner against oath-breakers) rather than the Solar Court inheritance.
Mainstream clerics working in Mafdet navigate two theologically distinct frameworks that share vocabulary but not doctrine: Solar Court theology treats divine law as cosmological maintenance; Mafdet theology treats it as oath-enforcement accountability.
Harbor Wardens' Ledger Houses require formal death documentation that cleric death rites satisfy for purposes of estate and claim resolution.
The swift-court's jurisdiction over oath-breaking creates demand for cleric oath-witnessing services that Mafdet-tradition clerics are better positioned to provide than Solar Court-tradition clerics.

flags MIDGAARD KHENARI
---
Khenari sacred record tradition and the cleric inner tradition share the deepest historical overlap of any race-class combination in the five-city network. Both descend from Solar Court practice: Khenari death-rite documentation requirements originated in the same Embalmer House and Jackal Tribunal culture that the cleric tradition's foundational lineage draws from.
Khenari clerics in Midgaard often carry awareness of both the outer tradition's public framework and inner tradition elements that the broader Khenari community maintains independently of the registry system.
The Sealed Names Apparatus's use of temple records as population tracking creates specific tension with Khenari spiritual privilege doctrine — Khenari clerics in Midgaard have been the most consistent institutional voices objecting to the practice on the grounds that the Apparatus is using Jackal Tribunal-tradition documentation for purposes the tradition explicitly prohibits.

flags KOWLOON USHABTI
---
Ushabti legal-standing doctrine applied to cleric practice produces a distinctive institutional position in Kowloon. Ushabti practitioners treat every significant action as generating claims that require adjudication. Cleric rites — consecration, oath-witnessing, death documentation — generate legally significant outcomes in Ushabti doctrine, which means Ushabti-trained clerics treat their professional practice as inherently legal rather than merely spiritual.
In Kowloon's Temple Circle governance structure, Ushabti clerics have argued successfully that temple records constitute evidence in dispute resolution proceedings — a position that the Jade Magistracy has formally accepted in several rulings, creating a productive intersection between Temple Circle documentation and Magistracy adjudication that other cities' frameworks do not produce.

